<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_BasisMaximalLinearlyIndependentSet"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Basis is maximal linearly independent set</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>A linearly independent subset <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> is a basis of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> if and only if , for every <math>
               <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
            </math> in <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math>, <math>
               <latex>T:= S\cup \Set{ \Vect{v} }</latex>
            </math> is not linearly independent.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>Consider first the case where <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is a basis of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. If <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}\in V</latex>
               </math>, we need to show that <math>
                  <latex>T:= S\cup \Set{ \Vect{v} }</latex>
               </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Indeed, we know that <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)=V</latex>
               </math>. So <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> is a linear combination of <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>:</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>x_1 \Vect{s}_1 + \cdots + x_k \Vect{s}_k</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>with <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{s}_1,\dots ,\Vect{s}_k</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. But then</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>-\Vect{v}\ +\ x_1 \Vect{s}_1 + \cdots + x_k \Vect{_k}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>is a representation of <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
               </math> by vectors in <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math> for which at least one coefficient is not 0. So <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math> is not linearly independent.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Consider next the case where, for every vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}\in V</latex>
               </math>, <math>
                  <latex>T:= S\cup \Set{ \Vect{v} }</latex>
               </math>  is dependent. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is a basis of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. Since we know already that <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is linearly independent, it only remains to show that <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)=V</latex>
               </math>. So let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}\in V</latex>
               </math> be arbitrary. Then <math>
                  <latex>T:= S\cup \Set{\Vect{v}}</latex>
               </math> is linearly dependent, implying that there is a linear combination</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t \Vect{v}\ +\ x_1 \Vect{s}_1 + \cdots + x_k \Vect{s}_k</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>with <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{s}_1,\dots ,\Vect{s}_k</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>, for which not all coefficients are 0. 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>We must have <math>
                        <latex>t=0</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>For suppose <math>
                              <latex>t=0</latex>
                           </math>. Then</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.array column="3">
                        <row rowspan="1">
                           <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>t</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                           <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                           <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>x_1 \Vect{s}_1 + \cdots + x_k \Vect{s}_k</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                        </row>
                     </math.array>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>is a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                              <latex>S</latex>
                           </math>. Since <math>
                              <latex>S</latex>
                           </math> is linearly independent, <math>
                              <latex>s_1=\cdots = s_k=0</latex>
                           </math>. So all coefficients are <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>, contradicting the hypotheses of the proposition.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>, implying that</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>(1/t) (x_1 \Vect{s}_1 + \cdots + x_k \Vect{s}_k)</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>is a linear combination of. â€“ This completes the proof.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
